{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>This entry represents the profilin family, which are small eukaryotic proteins that have different functions. In plants, they are major allergens present in pollens [[cite:PUB00063828]].</p>\n\n<p>The majority of the Profilin family members binds to monomeric actin (G-actin) in a 1:1 ratio thus preventing the polymerisation of actin into filaments (F-actin). They can also, in certain circumstances, promote actin polymerisation [[cite:PUB00071235]]. However, some profilin family members, such as Profilin 4 from mammals, does not bind to actin and may have functions distinct from regulating actin dynamics [[cite:PUB00071234]]. It plays a role in the assembly of branched actin filament networks, by activating WASP via binding to WASP's proline rich domain [[cite:PUB00081657]]. Profilin may link the cytoskeleton with major signalling pathways by interacting with components of the phosphatidylinositol cycle and Ras pathway [[cite:PUB00000725], [cite:PUB00018867]].</p>\n\n<p>This entry also includes Asgard archaeal profilins (Thor profilin, Loki profilin-1 and Loki profilin-2), which bind to actin and regulate the structure of the cytoskeleton. This indicates that Asgard archaea have a functional eukaryotic-like actin machinery [[cite:PUB00094554]].</p>\n\n<p>Some profilins can also bind to polyphosphoinositides such as PIP2 [[cite:PUB00063827]]. Overall sequence similarity among profilin from organisms which belong to different phyla (ranging from fungi to mammals) is low, but the N-terminal region is relatively well conserved. The N-terminal region is thought to be involved in actin binding.</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "3d9y", "name" "Crystal Structure of Profilin from Schizosaccharomyces pombe"}, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR036140", "name" "Profilin superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"pfam" {"PF00235" "Pro